definition.value: A 3-carboxy-2,3-dihydroxypropanoate that is the conjugate base of tartaric acid.
A benzazepine alkaloid isolated from Cephalotaxus harringtonia.
A chromium oxoanion resulting from the removal of two protons from chromic acid.
An oxoanion is an anion derived from an oxoacid by loss of hydron(s) bound to oxygen.
A compound containing at least one carbon-chromium bond.
A primary diamine is a compound derived from a hydrocarbon by replacing two hydrogen atoms by amino groups.
A primary diamine that is ethane or a higher alkane in which a hydrogen of each of the terminal methyl groups has been replaced by an amino group. H2NCH2(CH2)nCH2NH2, where n = 0, 1, 2, etc.
Compounds having two amino groups bonded to the same carbon, R2C(NR2)2.
An acetamide obtained by acetylation of one of the amino groups of any alkane-alpha,omega-diamine. AcNHCH2(CH2)nCH2NH2, where n = 0, 1, 2, etc.
Any alpha-amino-acid residue that is positively charged.
A ketoaldonate that is the conjugate base of N-acetylneuraminic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A steroid sulfate that is lithocholic acid in which the hydroxy hydrogen at position 3 has been replaced by a sulfo group.
An aryl sulfate the mono 4-nitrophenyl ester of sulfuric acid.
A ribose monophosphate that is D-ribose substituted at position 1 by a phosphate group.
One of three naturally occurring cephamycin antibiotics, differing from the A and B forms in its carbamoyloxymethyl substituent at C-3.
A member of the class of  hydroxybiphenyls formed formally by chlorination of biphenyl-4,4'-diol at C-3, -3', -5 and -5'.
An aminobiphenyl whose amino group is at C-4 and is hydroxylated at C-4'.
Any glucoside in which the glycoside group is derived from D-glucose.
A substance used in the prophylaxis or therapy of infectious diseases.
A substance used to treat or prevent parasitic infections.
Substance intended to kill parasitic worms (helminths).
